    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->
   <axiom component="lesson-plan">
    <title>Structured Instruction</title>
    <p>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the concepts and properties learners discovered in the anchor task.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </p>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Teacher Connection</title>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Group the measurements found by the class during the activity. Highlight that regardless of where point <m>C</m> was placed, the angle consistently measured exactly <m>90^\circ</m>. Formalize this as Thales's Theorem: <em>The angle subtended by a diameter at the circumference of a circle is always a right angle.</em>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                     Connect this back to the core circle theorem: <em>The angle subtended by an arc at the center is twice the angle subtended at the circumference</em>. Since a straight-line diameter forms a <m>180^\circ</m> angle at the center <m>O</m>, the angle at the circumference must be:
                    <me>\frac{180^\circ}{2} = 90^\circ</me>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </paragraphs>
</axiom>

<insight>
        <title>The Hidden Right-Triangle</title>
        <p>
            An inscribed triangle whose longest side is the <alert>diameter</alert> of a circle always forms a <alert>right angle (<m>90^\circ</m>)</alert> at the circumference. This property bridges circle geometry with:
            <ul>
                <li>The <alert>Pythagorean Theorem</alert> (<m>a^2 + b^2 = c^2</m>)</li>
                <li>Right-angle trigonometry ratios (<m>\sin, \cos, \tan</m>)</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- <insight>
    </insight> -->

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->
    <example>
    <!-- <title>Example 1: Finding a Missing Angle</title> -->
    <statement>
        <p>
            In a circle with center <m>O</m>, <m>PQ</m> is the diameter. A point <m>R</m> lies on the circumference such that <m>\angle RPQ = 34^\circ</m>. Determine the magnitude of <m>\angle PQR</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-circle-diameter-theorem">
    <caption>In a circle with diameter <m>PQ</m>, <m>\angle RPQ = 34^{\circ}</m>.</caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <description>A circle with center O and diameter PQ. A point R on the circumference forms a right-angled triangle PRQ with an angle of 34 degrees at vertex P.</description>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Centre and points on the circle ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}

            % Since PQ is the diameter, we place P and Q symmetrically across the center.
            % We can set P on the left (-180 deg) and Q on the right (0 deg).
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 180 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{P}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 0 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{Q}

            % Point R is on the circumference such that \angle RPQ = 34 degrees.
            % By circle geometry, the central angle \angle ROQ will be 2 * 34 = 68 degrees.
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 68 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{R}

            % Draw the circle through one of the points
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](O,Q)

            % --- Draw diameter, chords, and triangles ---
            \tkzDrawSegments(P,Q P,R Q,R)

            % --- Fill and mark the given and unknown angles ---
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,opacity=.6, size=.8](Q,P,R)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=orange!20,opacity=.6, size=.7](R,Q,P)
            
            % Thales's theorem angle (angle in a semicircle is 90 degrees)
            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=.3,color=black](P,R,Q)

            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.8,color=blue](Q,P,R)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.7,color=orange](R,Q,P)

            % --- Angle labels ---
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.2](Q,P,R){$34^{\circ}$}
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.1](R,Q,P){$?$}

            % --- Points and point labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints(O,P,Q,R)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below](O)
            \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
            \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above](R)

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Identify the angle subtended by the diameter: Since <m>PQ</m> is the diameter, <m>\angle PRQ = 90^\circ</m> (Angle subtended by diameter).
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Use the sum of angles in <m>\triangle PQR</m>:
            <me>\angle RPQ + \angle PRQ + \angle PQR = 180^\circ</me>
            <me>34^\circ + 90^\circ + \angle PQR = 180^\circ</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Solve for <m>\angle PQR</m>:
            <me>\angle PQR = 180^\circ - 124^\circ = 56^\circ</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example>
    <!-- <title>Example 2: Combining with Algebraic Expressions</title> -->
    <statement>
        <p>
            Line <m>AB</m> passes through the center <m>O</m> of a circle. Point <m>C</m> is on the circumference. If <m>\angle CAB = 2x</m> and <m>\angle CBA = 3x - 5^\circ</m>, find the value of <m>x</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-circle-diameter-algebra">
    <caption>Line <m>AB</m> passes through center <m>O</m> with <m>\angle CAB = 2x</m> and <m>\angle CBA = 3x - 5^{\circ}</m>.</caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <description>A circle with center O and diameter AB. A point C on the circumference forms a right-angled triangle ACB with algebraic expressions for the remaining angles.</description>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Centre and points on the circle ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}

            % Since AB is the diameter, we place A on the left (-180 deg) and B on the right (0 deg).
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 180 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{A}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 0 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{B}

            % Point C is on the circumference. Based on the geometry, angle CAB = 38 degrees.
            % The central angle COB will be 2 * 38 = 76 degrees.
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 76 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{C}

            % Draw the circle through one of the points
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](O,B)

            % --- Draw diameter, chords, and triangles ---
            \tkzDrawSegments(A,B A,C B,C)

            % --- Fill and mark the given and unknown angles ---
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,opacity=.6, size=.8](B,A,C)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=orange!20,opacity=.6, size=.7](C,B,A)
            
            % Thales's theorem angle (angle in a semicircle is 90 degrees)
            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=.3,color=black](A,C,B)

            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.8,color=blue](B,A,C)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.7,color=orange](C,B,A)

            % --- Angle labels ---
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.3](B,A,C){$2x$}
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.4](C,B,A){$3x - 5^{\circ}$}

            % --- Points and point labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints(O,A,B,C)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below](O)
            \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
            \tkzLabelPoints[right](B)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Since <m>AB</m> passes through the center <m>O</m>, it is a diameter. Therefore, <m>\angle ACB = 90^\circ</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Set up the interior angles equation for <m>\triangle ABC</m>:
            <me>2x + (3x - 5^\circ) + 90^\circ = 180^\circ</me>
            <me>5x + 85^\circ = 180^\circ</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Isolate <m>x</m>:
            <me>5x = 95^\circ</me>
            <me>x = 19^\circ</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example>
    <!-- <title>Example 3: Integrating the Pythagorean Theorem</title> -->
    <statement>
        <p>
            <m>XY</m> is the diameter of a circle with center <m>O</m>. Point <m>Z</m> is on the circumference such that chord <m>XZ = 6\text{ cm}</m> and chord <m>YZ = 8\text{ cm}</m>. Calculate the radius of the circle.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-circle-diameter-radius-calc">
    <caption>Diameter <m>XY</m> of a circle with center <m>O</m> and chords <m>XZ = 6\text{ cm}</m> and <m>YZ = 8\text{ cm}</m>.</caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <description>A circle with center O and horizontal diameter XY. A point Z on the circumference forms a right-angled triangle XZY, with chord XZ labeled 6 cm and chord YZ labeled 8 cm.</description>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Centre and points on the circle ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}

            % Since XY is the diameter, we place X on the left (-180 deg) and Y on the right (0 deg).
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 180 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{X}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 0 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{Y}

            % Point Z is placed on the circumference.
            % Based on the 6-8-10 right triangle, the central angle ZOY is exactly 106.26 degrees.
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 106.26 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{Z}

            % Draw the circle
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](O,Y)

            % --- Draw diameter and chords ---
            \tkzDrawSegments(X,Y X,Z Y,Z)

            % --- Mark the right angle at Z (angle in a semicircle) ---
            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=.3,color=black](X,Z,Y)

            % --- Segment labels (Chords) ---
            \tkzLabelSegment[above left,pos=0.5](X,Z){$6\text{ cm}$}
            \tkzLabelSegment[above right,pos=0.5](Y,Z){$8\text{ cm}$}

            % --- Points and point labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints(O,X,Y,Z)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below](O)
            \tkzLabelPoints[left](X)
            \tkzLabelPoints[right](Y)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above](Z)

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Because <m>XY</m> is the diameter, <m>\triangle XYZ</m> is a right-angled triangle with <m>\angle XZY = 90^\circ</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Apply the Pythagorean theorem to find the hypotenuse <m>XY</m>:
            <me>XY^2 = XZ^2 + YZ^2</me>
            <me>XY^2 = 6^2 + 8^2 = 36 + 64 = 100</me>
            <me>XY = \sqrt{100} = 10\text{ cm}</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. The diameter is <m>10\text{ cm}</m>, so the radius (<m>r</m>) is:
            <me>r = \frac{XY}{2} = \frac{10}{2} = 5\text{ cm}</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>
<example>
    <!-- <title>Example 4: The Circular Sports Field Shortcut</title> -->
    <statement>
        <p>
            A school has a perfectly circular sports field. A straight running track represents the diameter <m>AB</m> of the field. A student stands at a flagpost located at point <m>C</m> on the boundary fence. The student measures the angle from their position to the two endpoints of the diameter track. If <m>\angle CAB = 42^\circ</m>, calculate the angle <m>\angle CBA</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-circle-field-geometry">
    <caption>A circular sports field with diameter track <m>AB</m> and a flagpost at <m>C</m> on the boundary, where <m>\angle CAB = 42^{\circ}</m>.</caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <description>A circle representing a sports field with center O and diameter AB. A point C on the boundary fence forms a right-angled triangle ACB with an angle of 42 degrees at vertex A.</description>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Centre and points on the circle ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}

            % Since AB is the diameter, we place A on the left (-180 deg) and B on the right (0 deg).
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 180 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{A}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 0 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{B}

            % Point C is on the circumference. Given angle CAB = 42 degrees,
            % the central angle COB will be 2 * 42 = 84 degrees.
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 84 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{C}

            % Draw the circle
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](O,B)

            % --- Draw diameter and paths to the flagpost ---
            \tkzDrawSegments(A,B A,C B,C)

            % --- Fill and mark the given and unknown angles ---
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,opacity=.6, size=.8](B,A,C)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=orange!20,opacity=.6, size=.7](C,B,A)
            
            % Thales's theorem angle (angle in a semicircle is 90 degrees at the flagpost)
            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=.3,color=black](A,C,B)

            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.8,color=blue](B,A,C)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.7,color=orange](C,B,A)

            % --- Angle labels ---
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.2](B,A,C){$42^{\circ}$}
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.1](C,B,A){$?$}

            % --- Points and point labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints(O,A,B,C)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below](O)
            \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
            \tkzLabelPoints[right](B)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Identify the hidden geometric property: Because the running track <m>AB</m> is a diameter of the circular field, the angle subtended at the boundary point <m>C</m> must be a right angle. Therefore, <m>\angle ACB = 90^\circ</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Apply the interior angle sum theorem for <m>\triangle ABC</m>:
            <me>\angle CAB + \angle ACB + \angle CBA = 180^\circ</me>
            <me>42^\circ + 90^\circ + \angle CBA = 180^\circ</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Solve for the remaining angle <m>\angle CBA</m>:
            <me>\angle CBA = 180^\circ - 132^\circ = 48^\circ</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example>
    <!-- <title>Example 5: Structural Alignment of a Car Wheel Rim</title> -->
    <statement>
        <p>
            A mechanic uses a computer balancing alignment rig on a circular car wheel rim. The computer identifies a straight diameter line segment across the rim labeled <m>XY</m>. Two structural reinforcement spokes connect from points <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> to a single outer valve point <m>Z</m> on the edge of the rim. If the lengths of these spokes are represented by algebraic expressions where <m>\angle XZY = 5a - 10^\circ</m> and <m>\angle ZXY = 2a</m>, determine the value of <m>a</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-circle-rim-mechanic">
    <caption>A circular car wheel rim with diameter line segment <m>XY</m>, spokes to an outer valve point <m>Z</m>, where <m>\angle XZY = 5a - 10^{\circ}</m> and <m>\angle ZXY = 2a</m>.</caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <description>A circle representing a car rim with center O and diameter XY. A point Z on the circumference forms a right-angled triangle XZY with algebraic expressions for angles at Z and X.</description>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Centre and points on the circle ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}

            % Since XY is the diameter, we place X on the left (-180 deg) and Y on the right (0 deg).
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 180 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{X}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 0 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{Y}

            % Point Z is on the circumference. Based on the calculated angle ZXY = 40 degrees,
            % the central angle ZOY will be 2 * 40 = 80 degrees.
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 80 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{Z}

            % Draw the circle
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](O,Y)

            % --- Draw diameter and spokes ---
            \tkzDrawSegments(X,Y X,Z Y,Z)

            % --- Fill and mark the given and unknown angles ---
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=blue!20,opacity=.6, size=.8](Y,X,Z)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=orange!20,opacity=.6, size=.6](X,Z,Y)
            
            % Thales's theorem angle (angle in a semicircle is 90 degrees)
            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=.3,color=black](X,Z,Y)

            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.8,color=blue](Y,X,Z)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=orange](X,Z,Y)

            % --- Angle labels ---
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.2](Y,X,Z){$2a$}
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.2](X,Z,Y){$5a - 10^{\circ}$}

            % --- Points and point labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints(O,X,Y,Z)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below](O)
            \tkzLabelPoints[left](X)
            \tkzLabelPoints[right](Y)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above](Z)

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Apply Thales's Theorem to the wheel setup: Since <m>XY</m> is the diameter of the circular rim, the angle subtended at the outer valve point <m>Z</m> on the circumference must equal <m>90^\circ</m>.
            <me>\angle XZY = 90^\circ</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Equate the expression to find the scalar variable <m>a</m>:
            <me>5a - 10^\circ = 90^\circ</me>
            <me>5a = 100^\circ</me>
            <me>a = 20^\circ</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Check consistency using the remaining angle <m>\angle ZXY</m>:
            <me>\angle ZXY = 2(20^\circ) = 40^\circ</me>
            The setup remains a valid right-angled triangle since the acute angles sum up to <m>90^\circ</m> (<m>40^\circ + 50^\circ = 90^\circ</m>).
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A packaging engineer designs a novelty triangular pizza slice box that fits exactly inside a semi-circular transparent lid. The straight baseline of the box is the diameter <m>MN</m> of the circle and measures <m>13\text{ cm}</m>. The vertex corner of the pizza slice touches the curved lid edge at point <m>P</m>. If the shorter cardboard side wall <m>MP</m> is <m>5\text{ cm}</m> long, calculate the length of the remaining side wall <m>NP</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-circle-pizza-box">
    <caption>A triangular pizza box inside a semicircular lid with diameter <m>MN = 13\text{ cm}</m> and side <m>MP = 5\text{ cm}</m>.</caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <description>A circle with center O and horizontal diameter MN representing the box baseline. A point P on the circumference forms a right-angled triangle MPN representing the pizza slice, with side MP labeled 5 cm and diameter MN labeled 13 cm.</description>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Centre and points on the circle ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}

            % Since MN is the diameter, we place M on the left (-180 deg) and N on the right (0 deg).
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 180 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{M}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 0 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{N}

            % Point P is on the circumference. Based on the 5-12-13 right triangle,
            % the central angle PON is exactly 134.76 degrees.
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 134.76 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{P}

            % Draw the circle
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](O,N)

            % --- Draw diameter and chords ---
            \tkzDrawSegments(M,N M,P N,P)

            % --- Mark the right angle at P (angle in a semicircle) ---
            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=.3,color=black](M,P,N)

            % --- Segment labels ---
            \tkzLabelSegment[above left,pos=0.5](M,P){$5\text{ cm}$}
            \tkzLabelSegment[above right,pos=0.5](N,P){$?$}
            \tkzLabelSegment[below,pos=0.5](M,N){$13\text{ cm}$}

            % --- Points and point labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints(O,M,N,P)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below](O)
            \tkzLabelPoints[left](M)
            \tkzLabelPoints[right](N)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above](P)

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Establish the right-angle framework: Because the baseline <m>MN</m> is the diameter of the circle, the triangle <m>\triangle MNP</m> formed within the semi-circle is right-angled at the circumference vertex. Thus, <m>\angle MPN = 90^\circ</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Use the Pythagorean theorem to calculate side wall <m>NP</m>, where diameter <m>MN</m> acts as the hypotenuse:
            <me>MN^2 = MP^2 + NP^2</me>
            <me>13^2 = 5^2 + NP^2</me>
            <me>169 = 25 + NP^2</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Isolate and solve for <m>NP</m>:
            <me>NP^2 = 169 - 25 = 144</me>
            <me>NP = \sqrt{144} = 12\text{ cm}</me>
            The length of the remaining cardboard side wall is <m>12\text{ cm}</m>.
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>
